  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" class="fn" id="_ftn1">[1]</a> <i>In re Lieberman</i>,
  95-2628 (La. 6/7/96); 675 So. 2d 272.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" class="fn" id="_ftn2">[2]</a> <i>In re Quaid</i>, 94-1316
  (La. 11/30/94); 646 So.2d 343, 350.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" class="fn" id="_ftn3">[3]</a> The applicable ABA Standard
  relative to the violation of Rule 1.7(a) is:</p>

  <blockquote>
    <p class="footnotetext"><span class="ABAstandard">4.32</span>  Suspension is generally appropriate when a lawyer
    knows of a conflict of interest and does not fully disclose to a client the possible effect of that conflict, and
    causes injury or potential injury to a client.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">Depending on whether the conduct was knowing or negligent, the applicable ABA Standard for
    a violation of Rules 1.3 and 1.4(a) is:</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><span class="ABAstandard">4.42</span>  Suspension is generally appropriate when:</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">(a) a lawyer knowingly fails to perform services for a client and causes injury or
    potential injury to a client . . . ;</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">or</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><span class="ABAstandard">4.43</span>  Reprimand is generally appropriate when a lawyer is
    negligent and does not act with reasonable diligence in representing a client, and causes injury or potential
    injury to a client.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">Depending on whether respondent's failure to properly terminate his representation was
    knowing or negligent, the applicable ABA Standard is:</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><span class="ABAstandard">7.2</span>  Suspension is generally appropriate when a lawyer
    knowingly engages in conduct that is a violation of a duty owed to the profession and causes injury or potential
    injury to a client, the public, or the legal system.</p>

    <p class="footnotetext">or</p>

    <p class="footnotetext"><span class="ABAstandard">7.3</span>  Reprimand is generally appropriate when a lawyer
    negligently engages in conduct that is a violation of a duty owed to the profession and causes injury or potential
    injury to a client, the public, or the legal system.</p>
  </blockquote>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4" class="fn" id="_ftn4">[4]</a> <i>In re Caulfield, supra</i>
  at 719. </p>
